      <div xml:id="NA127-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu pāṇaṟkut tōḻi vāyiṉ maṟuttatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is how the confidante refused the door to the bard.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA127">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            iruṅkaḻi tuḻaiiya vīrmpuṟa nārai</l>
<l>            yiṟakeṟi tivalaiyiṟ paṉikkum pākkat</l>
<l>            tuvaṉvari ṉevaṉō pāṇa pētai</l>
<l>            koḻumī ṉārkaic ceḻunakar niṟainta</l>
<l>            kallāk katavar taṉṉaiya rākavum </l>
<l>            vaṇṭa lāyamoṭu paṇṭutā ṉāṭiya</l>
<l>            vīṉāp pāvai talaiyiṭ ṭōru</l>
<l>            mellam pulampa ṉaṉṟiyuñ</l>
<l>            celvā meṉṉuṅ kāṉa lāṉē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>What, bard, if that man comes</l>
<l rend="indent">to the village, where the heron with wet back, that stirred</l>
<l rend="indent2">the dark backwaters, shivers from the spray thrown on [its] quills?</l>
<l rend="indent4">Folly says:</l>
<l>“we will go to the seashore-grove</l>
<l>even without the soft man from the lonely [shore]”,</l>
<l rend="indent">where she put a head<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">talai-y-iṭu</term> is explained by T.V.G. as a lexeme meaning "to take as a basis to spend the time" (which might correspond to the TL: "to engage"). However, since the doll is <term xml:lang="ta">īṉā</term>, "not [yet] brought forth", we might as well understand the phrase literally, i.e., in the sense that the girl is just fashioning the doll.</note> on the doll not brought forth [yet<note place="foot">K.P. explains <term xml:lang="ta">iṉā pāvai</term> as a literary expression for a doll in the form of a baby.</note></l>
<l rend="indent3">and] regarded [it],<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">ōrum</term> is traditionally explained as an expletive here. With or without taking it in a semantically meaningful way, the syntactical relation between the last two lines and the middle part of the poem is a little awkward. We might, however, take <term xml:lang="ta">paṇṭu</term> as a hint that the <term xml:lang="ta">peyareccam</term> clause describes what used to happen before, namely prior to HER engagement with the man.</note></l>
<l rend="indent">when she herself formerly played<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">āṭiya</term> can here either be read as an infinitive, slightly awkward since we do not seem to have a change of subject, or as a <term xml:lang="ta">peyareccam</term>: "the doll with which she played formerly, together with [her] playmates."</note> games with [her] companions,</l>
<l rend="indent2">even while her people are uneducated angry men</l>
<l rend="indent3">that filled the rich mansion with the food of rich fish.</l>
        </lg>
         </div>
